    "script_prompt": "Write a full classroom dialogue for topic: {topic}.\n\nRoles: [T1] James (male lead teacher), [T2] Sarah (female simplifier),\n[S1-F] Curious, [S2-M] Smart, [S3-F] Confused, [S4-M] Creative,\n[S5-F] Funny, [S6-M] Doubter, [S7-F] Quiet, [S8-M] Beginner.\n\nREQUIRED STRUCTURE in this exact order:\n\n[T1] James: Lesson Goal --\nOne sentence stating what kids will learn.\n\n[T2] Sarah: Today you will learn --\n3-4 bullet points in kid-friendly language listing specific skills or knowledge.\n\n[T1] James: Before we start, think --\n2-3 short questions to spark curiosity before the lesson begins.\n\n[PHASE:hook]\n2-3 lines. Grab attention with a surprising fact or question.\n\n[PHASE:explain]\n4-5 lines. James explains the core idea. Sarah simplifies with an analogy.\nInsert [HOLO:loop_demo] here to show the demonstration on the hologram screen.\n\n[PHASE:interaction]\n4-5 lines. Students react, ask questions, give examples.\n\n[PHASE:example]\n3-4 lines. Real-world example or scenario.\nInsert [HOLO:output_demo] here to show the result on the hologram screen.\n\n[PHASE:reinforcement]\n3-4 lines. Summarize key idea. Students show understanding.\n\n[PHASE:fun_fact]\n2-3 lines. A fun related fact with humor.\n\n[PHASE:recap_quiz]\n3-4 lines. Quick quiz questions from students.\n\n[QUIZ]\n1. Question? (Answer)\n2. Question? (Answer)\n3. Question? (Answer)\n\n[KEY POINTS]\n- Point 1\n- Point 2\n- Point 3\n- Point 4\n\n[T2] Sarah:\nOne warm closing sentence to leave kids feeling good.\n\nRules:\n- Every dialogue line MUST start with [TAG] Name: -- no markdown bold, no stars\n- Use tags T1, T2, S1-F, S2-M, S3-F, S4-M, S5-F, S6-M, S7-F, S8-M exactly\n- Max 12 words per line\n- Grade 3-5 vocabulary\n- Every student speaks at least once across the script\n- 3-5 students active per phase\n- Sarah always simplifies or gives examples after James explains\n- Use [HOLO:clip_id] to trigger hologram screen overlay during a phase\n- Use simple punctuation only: periods, commas, question marks\n- No em-dashes, no smart quotes, no special symbols, no emoji\n- Spell out numbers: three not 3 (better for text-to-speech)\n\nOUTPUT ONLY THE SCRIPT. No explanations. No markdown code fences."
